Slovenian Prime Minister: Antifa Is ‘International Terrorist Organisation’

Janez Janša, prime minister of former first lady Melania Trump’s home country of Slovenia, has labelled the far-left extremist group Antifa an “international terrorist organisation” following violence in France over the weekend

Prime Minister Janša made his comments on social media network Twitter, saying: “Antifa is a global terrorist organization. Supported by the capital of financial speculators forging profits at the expense of the chaos caused by the operation.”

The Slovenian leader was reacting to a post by American journalist Andy Ngo which highlighted Antifa violence over the weekend in the French city of Nantes which saw the far-left extremists attempt to disrupt a meeting of the conservative writer and French presidential hopeful Eric Zemmour.

According to a report from the newspaper Le Figaro, around 600 far-left extremists gathered in Nantes to oppose Zemmour on Saturday and some chanted for his death and clashed with police.

“We know who Joseph Stalin was, we know the hundreds of thousands of deaths he caused, these people are only his distant descendants,” Zemmour said in reaction to the far-left extremists.

Footage of the violence, as well as graffiti calling for Zemmour to be murdered, was reported by French journalist Clément Lanot.

Prime Minister Janez Janša is not the first world leader to label Antifa as a terrorist group. Former U.S. President Donald J. Trump urged former Secretary of State Mike Pompeo to designate Antifa as a terrorist group earlier this year before leaving office.

The year prior, former U.S. Attorney General William Barr stated that Antifa members were involved in violence that amounted to domestic terrorism.

“The violence instigated and carried out by Antifa and other similar groups in connection with the rioting is domestic terrorism and will be treated accordingly,” Barr said.

In 2019, when President Trump first discussed declaring Antifa a terrorist group, left-wing figures across Europe, particularly in Germany, reacted by declaring their support for the extremist group.

Here Are A Few Child Custody Issues To Assist You In Preparing For Court

As you prepare to gain custody of your kid in court, there are several issues to consider. Fathers have a greater difficulty getting custody than mothers, but this isn't always the case. Here is a child custody checklist to assist you in preparing for court.

1. Hire a really good child custody attorney. Make sure they are experienced in your specific needs and get references.

2. Make a list of your ex-wife's weaknesses. This will only help you in your case against her. If you have facts about her that will prove her to be an unfit mother, and then, by all means, use them to your advantage.

3. Make a list of your ex-wife's strengths. This may sound obviously odd at first, but it will help you prepare to go against her in court. If you know her strengths, you'll know how to counter them in court.

4. Get a list of witnesses that could testify on your behalf (basically telling the judge how you are a great father). Also, get a list of witnesses to testify against your ex-wife if need be. If you don't feel she's a fit mother, then have others prove your case for you.

5. Decide if now is the right time to start dating someone else. The divorce process is a long one, and sometimes the judge will frown on you if you already have a live-in girlfriend.

6. Make sure you have health and life insurance in place for your child, and make sure you are the one that took out the policies. This will show the judge you are the responsible parent.

7. Sit down with your child custody attorney and make a list of important things you may not openly share with people; Things like arrests, bankruptcies, affairs, fights, everything. You don't want any surprises in court. If you inform your child custody attorney of these things in advance, he'll be able to work up a defense for them as well.

Le Kansas se joint à l'action en justice pour poursuivre l'administration Biden sur le mandat du vaccin COVID-19

COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) - Dix-huit États ont intenté trois procès distincts vendredi pour empêcher le président Joe Biden de rendre obligatoire le vaccin COVID-19 pour les entrepreneurs fédéraux, en faisant valoir que cette exigence viole la loi fédérale.

Les procureurs généraux de l'Alaska, de l'Arkansas, de l'Iowa, du Missouri, du Montana, du Nebraska, du New Hampshire, du Dakota du Nord, du Dakota du Sud et du Wyoming ont signé l'une des actions en justice, qui a été déposée devant un tribunal fédéral de district du Missouri. Un autre groupe d'États comprenant la Géorgie, l'Alabama, l'Idaho, le Kansas, la Caroline du Sud, l'Utah et la Virginie occidentale a déposé une plainte devant un tribunal fédéral de district en Géorgie.

Le Texas a également intenté une action individuelle vendredi.

Les États ont demandé à un juge fédéral de bloquer l'exigence de M. Biden selon laquelle tous les employés des entreprises fédérales doivent être vaccinés contre le coronavirus d'ici le 8 décembre, en faisant valoir que le mandat viole la loi fédérale sur les marchés publics et constitue un excès de pouvoir fédéral.

"Si le gouvernement fédéral tente d'exercer sa volonté de manière inconstitutionnelle et de forcer les contractants fédéraux à rendre les vaccinations obligatoires, la main-d'œuvre et les entreprises pourraient être décimées, ce qui aggraverait encore la crise de la chaîne d'approvisionnement et de la main-d'œuvre", a déclaré dans un communiqué le procureur général du Missouri, Eric Schmitt, un républicain. "Le gouvernement fédéral ne devrait pas rendre les vaccinations obligatoires, et c'est pourquoi nous avons intenté un procès aujourd'hui - pour mettre fin à cette action illégale et anticonstitutionnelle."

"Aucun Américain ne devrait être menacé par son gouvernement fédéral de perdre son emploi parce que ses décisions en matière de santé diffèrent de celles que préfère le président des États-Unis", a déclaré le procureur général du Kansas, Derek Schmidt. "Rien dans la Constitution américaine n'autorise ce genre d'intrusion sans précédent du gouvernement fédéral dans les décisions personnelles de soins de santé de millions de travailleurs américains, et à notre avis, le président ne possède certainement pas le pouvoir de le décréter de lui-même."

Le procureur général républicain du New Hampshire, John Formella, a déclaré dans un communiqué que les vaccins COVID sont sûrs, efficaces et encouragés, mais que les avantages "ne justifient pas de violer la loi."
